<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-03-19T09:56:13-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-03-19T09:56:13-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6193&amp;p=58633#p58633</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6193&amp;p=58633#p58633"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NOP taking many addressing modes, is that so?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6193&amp;p=58633#p58633"><![CDATA[
Remember, there are no illegal opcodes, only unofficial ones. When the NES encounters one, it doesn't stop or turn off; it does <em>something</em>. Put another way, if a Martian recovered a NES without any software and reverse-engineered it in its entirety, he'd make no distinction between the official and unofficial instructions. They'd all simply be things the CPU did in response to a particular pattern in the opcode.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Fri Mar 19, 2010 9:56 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
